019 \n|<!-- Title -->  ''When Angels Sing: The Story of Rock Legend Carlos Santana''\n|<!-- Author --> {{sort|Mahin, Michael |Michael Mahin}}\n|<!-- Illustrator --> {{sort|Ramirez, Jose |Jose Ramirez}}\n|<!-- Publisher --> [[Atheneum Books]]\n|<!-- Citation --> Commended\n|}\n\n==Recipients of Multiple Awards and Honors==\n<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER WITHIN EACH SECTION -->\n\n===Multiple Am\u00e9ricas Awards===\nOne person's works have received four Am\u00e9ricas Awards:\n* [[Margarita Engle]], as author in 2006, 2009, 2012, and 2015.\n\nOne person's works have received three Am\u00e9ricas Awards:\n*[[Duncan Tonatiuh]], as author and illustrator in 2015, 2018, and 2019.\n\nMultiple people's works have won two Am\u00e9ricas Awards: \n* As author and illustrator: [[Yuyi Morales]].\n* As author: [[Julia Alvarez]], [[Monica Brown (author)|Monica Brown]], [[Juan Felipe Herrera]], [[Francisco Jim\u00e9nez (writer)|Francisco Jim\u00e9nez]], [[Lynn Joseph]] and [[Pam Mu\u00f1oz Ryan]].\n\n===Multiple Am\u00e9ricas Honors===\nMultiple people's works have received two honors: \n* As author and illustrator: [[Maya Christina Gonzalez|Maya Christina Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Yuyi Morales]], and  [[Duncan Tonatiuh]]\n* As illustrator [[David D\u00edaz (illustrator)|David D\u00edaz]]\n* As author: [[Margarita Engle]], [[Judith Ortiz Cofer]], and Laura Resau\n\n===Multiple Am\u00e9ricas Commendations===\nDifferent works by the same authors or illustrators have received commendations in the same year.\n\nTwo people's work has received commendations nine times:\n* [[George Ancona]] as both author and illustrator in 1994, 1995, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2003, 2007-2008, and 2011.\n* Maya Christina Gonz\u00e1lez as illustrator twice in 1997, and once 1998, 1999, 2001, 2002, 2007-2008, and 2009; and as author and illustrator in 2007-2008.\n\nThree people's work has received commendations eight times:\n* [[Jorge Argueta]] as author in 2003, twice in 2006, 2007-2008, 2010, 2011, 2016, and 2017.\n* [[Margarita Engle]] as author in 2010, 2014, twice in 2016, 2017, twice in 2018, and 2019.\n* [[Gary Soto]] as author in 1995, twice in 1997, twice in 1998, 2003, 2006, and 2009.\n\nTwo people's work has received commendations seven times:\n* [[Alma Flor Ada]] as author in 1995, twice in 1997, 1998, 2002, and 2016.\n* [[Pat Mora]] as author in 1996, 1997, 2002, twice in 2010, and 2011.\n\nTwo people's works have received commendations six times:\n* David D\u00edaz as illustrator in 1996, 2000, 2002, 2010, 2011, and 2016.\n* Enrique O. S\u00e1nchez as illustrator in 1993, 1994, twice in 1996, 1997, and 1999.\n\nFour people's works have received commendations five times:\n* [[Francisco X. Alarc\u00f3n]] as author in 1997, 1998, 1999, 2001, and 2009.\n* [[Monica Brown (author)|Monica Brown]] as author in 2007-2008, 2010, 2014, 2016, and 2018.\n* Ra\u00fal Col\u00f3n as illustrator in 1997, 2005, 2007-2008, and twice in 2015.\n* Francisco X. Stork as author in 2006, 2010, 2011, 2017, and 2018.\n\nEight people's works have received commendations four times:\n* Lori Marie Carlson as author in 1994, 1996, 2005, and 2009.\n* [[Lulu Delacre]] as illustrator in 1994 and 1997; as author in 1996; and author and illustrator in 2000.\n* Domi as illustrator in 2006, 2006, 2009, and 2011.\n* Arthur Dorros as author and illustrator in 1993 and 1995, and as author in 2005 and 2015.\n* Tony Johnston\tas author in 1994, 1997, 2001, and 2010.\n* [[Rafael L\u00f3pez (illustrator and artist)|Rafael L\u00f3pez]] as illustrator in 2010, 2014, 2016, and 2018.\n* Edel Rodr\u00edguez as illustrator in 2001, 2010, and twice in 2016.\n* [[Benjamin Alire S\u00e1enz]] as author in twice in 2009, 2013, and 2018. \n\nTwenty people's works have received commendations three times:\n* [[Rudolfo Anaya]] as author in 1995, 2000, and 2004.\n* [[Carmen Bernier-Grand|Carmen T. Bernier-Grand]] as author in 1994, 2007-2008, and 2010.\n* [[Robert Casilla]] as illustrator in 1993, 1996, and 2004.\n* Joe Cepeda as illustrator in 1998, 2007-2008, and 2011.\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Colato La\u00ednez]] as author in 2010, 2011, and 2017. \n* Amy C\u00f3rdova as illustrator in 2004, 2009, and 2011.\n* [[Tomie dePaola]] as author and illustrator in 1994, and as illustrator in 1994 and 1999.\n* Luis Garay as illustrator in 1996 and 2007-2008, and as author and illustrator in 1997.\n* Phillis Gershator as author twice in 1994 and once in 1998.\n* [[Juan Felipe Herrera]] as author in 1995, 2002, and 2015. \n* [[Francisco Jim\u00e9nez (writer)|Francisco Jim\u00e9nez]] as author in 1998, 2000, and 2009.\n* [[Elisa Kleven]] as illustrator in 1994 and 1997, and author and illustrator in 1996. \n* [[Georgina L\u00e1zaro]] as author in 2009, 2010, and 2018.\n* Fran\u00e9 Lessac as author and illustrator in 1994, and as illustrator in 1994 and 2013.\n* [[Meg Medina]] as author in 2014, 2017, and 2019.\n* Roseanne Greenfield Thong as author in 2014 and twice in 2015. \n* [[Duncan Tonatiuh]] as author and illustrator in 2011 and 2017, and as illustrator in 2016.\n* Beatriz Vidal as illustrator in 1998, 2002, and 2018.\n* [[Jeanette Winter]] as illustrator in 1997, and as author and illustrator in 2007-2008 and 2011.\n* Rafael Yockteng as illustrator in 2002, 2010, and 2016.\n\n\nMultiple people's work has received two commendations: \n* As author and illustrator: Angela Dominguez, Laura Lac\u00e1mara, [[Yuyi Morales]], and Leyla Torres.\n* As illustrator: Jamel Akib, Renato Alarc\u00e3o, Andrea Arroyo, Martha Avil\u00e9s, Claire B. Cotts, Felipe D\u00e1valos, Carla Golembe, [[Ann Grifalconi]], [[Holly Meade]], John Parra, [[Ra\u00fal the Third]], Alfonso Ruano, [[Synthia Saint James]], Elivia Savadier, Sim\u00f3n Silva.\n* As author: [[Eve Bunting]], [[Cathy Camper]], Teresa C\u00e1rdenas, Pablo Cartaya, Omar S. Casta\u00f1eda,  [[Matt de la Pe\u00f1a]], Campbell Geeslin, Mary-Joan Gerson, [[Lucia M. Gonzalez|Luc\u00eda M. Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Rigoberta Mench\u00fa]], [[Jose-Luis Orozco]], Amada Irma P\u00e9rez, [[Isabel Quintero]], Vashanti Rahaman, Antonio Ram\u00edrez, Laura Resau, Roni Capin Rivera-Ashford, [[Carmen Tafolla]], Erika Tamar, Nancy Van Laan, and Jonah Winter.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Awards established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Children's literary awards]]\n[[Category:Young adult literature awards]]\n[[Category:Latin American literary awards]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American culture]]\n[[Category:American children's literary awards]]\n[[Category:Literary awards honoring minority groups]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American literature]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox award\n| name           = Am\u00e9ricas Award\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = 250px\n| caption        = \n| description    = Encourage and commend authors, illustrators and publishers who produce quality children\u2019s and young adult books that portray Latin America, the Caribbean, or Latinos in the United States, and to provide teachers with recommendations for classroom use\n| presenter      = Consortium of Latin American Studies Programs, coordinated by [[Tulane University|Tulane University\u2019s]] Stone Center for Latin American Studies and [[Vanderbilt University|Vanderbilt University\u2019s]] Center for Latin American Studies\n| country        = United States\n| year           = 1993\n| website        = {{URL|claspprograms.org/americasaward}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Am\u00e9ricas Award for Children\u2019s and Young Adult Literature''' is [[literary award]] presented annually that recognizes high quality \"children\u2019s and young adult books that portray Latin America, the Caribbean, or Latinos in the United States, and to provide teachers with recommendations for classroom use.\" It was first awarded in 1993 by the Consortium of Latin American Studies Programs (CLASP).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.claspprograms.org/americasaward|title=Americas Award @ CLASP|last=|first=|date=|website=Consortium of Latin American Studies Programs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> The award is presented annually at a ceremony at the Library of Congress during Hispanic Heritage Month, along with coordinating workshops for teachers. <ref name=\"ceremony\">{{cite web |title=Award Ceremony |url=http://claspprograms.org/pages/detail/69/Award-Ceremony |website=CLASP |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref> \n\n== History ==\nThe Am\u00e9ricas Award was proposed in 1992 within the Teaching and Outreach Committee of the Consortium of Latin American Studies Programs.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/933386001|title=The Am\u00e9ricas Award : honoring Latin@ children's and young adult literature of the Americas|last=Quiroa|first=Ruth|publisher=Lexington Books|others=|year=2016|isbn=978-1-4985-0160-6|editor-last=Henderson|editor-first=Laretta|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=30|chapter=Envisioning tomorrow : the musings of Julie Kline on the history and future of the Am\u00e9ricas Award|oclc=933386001}}</ref> Julie Kline, at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Milwaukee]], served as the committee chair for the first 3 years of the award and then went on to be the award coordinator for many years.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/933386001|title=The Am\u00e9ricas Award : honoring Latin@ children's and young adult literature of the Americas|last=Quiroa|first=Ruth|publisher=Lexington Books|others=|year=2016|isbn=978-1-4985-0160-6|editor-last=Henderson|editor-first=Laretta|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=33|chapter=Envisioning tomorrow : the musings of Julie Kline on the history and future of the Am\u00e9ricas Award|oclc=933386001}}</ref> Coordination for the award later moved to Latin American Studies centers at [[Tulane University|Tulane]] and [[Vanderbilt University|Vanderbilt Universities]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/933386001|title=The Am\u00e9ricas Award : honoring Latin@ children's and young adult literature of the Americas|last=Henderson|first=Laretta|publisher=Lexington Books|others=|year=2016|isbn=978-1-4985-0160-6|editor-last=Henderson|editor-first=Laretta|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=5|chapter=The Am\u00e9ricas Award: Latin@ Youth Literature for the K-12 Classroom|oclc=933386001}}</ref> A full research collection of all winning, honor, and commended titles is kept and maintained by the University of Wisconsin\u2013Milwaukee at the [[Golda Meir Library]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=Research Collection |url=http://www.claspprograms.org/pages/detail/76/Research-Collection |website=CLASP |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Curriculum Collection Book Lists: Am\u00e9ricas Collection |url=https://guides.library.uwm.edu/CCM_booklists |website=University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Criteria and Eligibility==\nThe award judges will evaluate books based on \n# Distinctive literary quality;  \n# Cultural contextualization; \n# Exceptional integration of text, illustration and design; \n# Potential for classroom use. <ref name=\"criteria\">{{cite web |title=The Am\u00e9ricas Award for Children\u2019s and Young Adult Literature |url=https://as.vanderbilt.edu/clas/americas-award/  |publisher=Vanderbilt University |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn order to be eligible for the award, a title must meet the following criteria:\n* The book must be published in the preceding year.\n* The title may be for primary or secondary reading levels.\n* Language of publication may be English, Spanish, Portuguese, or any language indigenous to the Americas.\n* The book must be published in the United States or by a publisher with offices within the U.S.\n* Submissions may be fiction, poetry, folklore, or selected non-fiction.\n* A book will only be considered in its first year of publication in the United States. A book originally published in the U.S. in English with a translated edition in a subsequent year will only be eligible the first year of the edition. <ref name=\"guidelines\">{{cite web |title=Nomination Guidelines |url=http://claspprograms.org/pages/detail/67/Nomination-Guidelines |website=Americas Award |publisher=CLASP |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Recipients==\n<!--\n|- \n| year\n| {{sort|title, The|''[[title]]''}}\n| {{sort|last, first|[[first last]]}}\n| {{sort|last, first|[[first last]]}}\n| citation (Winner, Honor, Commended)\n-->\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+ Am\u00e9ricas Award Recipients, Honorable Mentions, and Commended books <ref name=\"books\">{{cite web |title=Award Winners |url=http://www.claspprograms.org/pages/detail/68/Award-Winners |website=Americas Award |publisher=CLASP |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n!width=\"5%\"|Year\n!width=\"25%\"|Title\n!width=\"20%\"|Author\n!width=\"20%\"|Illustrator\n!width=\"20%\"|Publisher\n!width=\"10%\"|Citation\n|- style=\"background:LemonChiffon; color:black\"\n|<!-- Year --> 1993\n|<!-- Title --> ''Vejigante Masquerader''\n|<!-- Author --> {{sort|delacre, lulu|[[Lulu Delacre]]}}\n|<!-- Illustrator --> {{sort|delacre, lulu|[[Lulu Delacre]]}}\n|<!-- Publisher --> [[Scholastic Press|Scholastic]]\n|<!-- Citation --> Winner\n|- \n|<!-- Year --> 1993\n|<!-- Title --> ''Abuela's Weave''\n|<!-- Author --> {{sort|castaneda, omar s.|Omar S. Casta\u00f1eda}}\n|<!-- Illustrator --> {{sort|sanchez, enrique o|Enrique O. S\u00e1nchez}}\n|<!-- Publisher --> [[Lee & Low Books]]\n|<!-- Citation --> Commended\n|- \n|<!-- Year --> 1993\n|<!-- Title --> ''Celebrating the Hero''\n|<!-- Author --> {{sort|becerra de jenkins, lyll |Lyll Becerra de Jenkins}}\n|<!-- Illustrator --> \n|<!-- Publisher --> [[Lodestar Books]]\n|<!-- Citation --> Commended\n|- \n|<!-- Year --> 1993\n|<!-- Title --> ''For the Life of Laetitia''\n|<!-- Author --> {{sort|hodge, herle|[[Merle Hodge]]}}\n|<!-- Illustrator --> \n|<!-- Publisher --> [[Farrar, Straus & Giroux]]\n|<!-- Citation --> Commended\n|- \n|<!-- Year --> 1993\n|<!-- Title -->